</SCRIPT>
March 11, 2006 </P>
<P><B>SAFIN WINS IN STRAIGHT SETS: </B>Down a break early in the first set, unseeded Marat Safin answered back with two breaks to take the first set and he picked up where he left off after a rain delay to defeat Amer Delic 6-3, 6-4. 
<P>"I felt pretty good. It was tough conditions," Safin said. "The knee was OK that's the most important thing." 
<P>Sidelined with his knee injury, Safin played in only one tournament in the final five months of 2005, and he skipped the Australian tournaments in January so he missed out on the chance to defend his 2005 Australian Open championship. The Russian returned to action at Dubai where he lost in the round of 16. All of those missed tournaments over the past year dropped him from fourth to 53rd in the rankings. 
<P>"In my position right now I can just hope to play as many tournaments as I can, so at least I can get my ranking back," Safin said. "I was coming here and just trying to play as many matches as I can." 
<P>Safin passed on surgery and chose instead to nurse his knee back to health through physical therapy in Moscow. He said surgeons warned him that if he underwent an operation he risked ending his tennis career. 
<P>"They told me, 'Don't do the operation. Do the procedure, physical therapy, ultrasound, laser, all these things. At least you can play a little bit, but if you have the operation and something goes wrong then, you just forget about tennis,'" he said.</P></td>
